Week 8B: JAGS Intro

If you have not installed the following packages you need to install them: rjags, R2jags, runjags, MCMCpack

library(R2jags)
library(lattice)

We will define a model using JAGS language. We will use the simple regression model from last class, where for \(i = 1, ... , n\), \[\begin{align*} y_i & \sim \textrm{N} (\alpha + \beta(x_i -\overline{x}), \sigma^2) \\ \alpha & \sim \textrm{N}(0, 10^4) \\ \beta & \sim \textrm{N}(0, 10^4) \\ \sigma^{-2} & \sim \textrm{Ga}(0.1, 0.1) \end{align*}\]

Now, we write this model in Jags.

linear.model.JAGS = function(){
  for(i in 1:n){
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i],tau2)
    mu[i]<- alpha + beta*(x[i]-x.bar) 
  }
  x.bar <- mean(x)
  alpha ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0E-4)
  beta ~ dnorm(0.0, 1.0E-4)
  sigma2 <- 1.0/tau2
  tau2 ~ dgamma(0.1,0.1)
}

Next, we need some data to fit the model to. We will simulate the following data.

n = 100
x = rnorm(n,mean = 3.0, sd = 1)
y = 1.0 + 2.0*(x-3.0) + rnorm(n, 0, sd=0.5)
data.JAGS = list(y = y, x = x, n = n)

We also need to set the initial values of our Markov chain. The following contains two options. First, the parameter coefficients are set to 0 with unit precision. Second, the initial values are selected randomly.

inits.JAGS = list(list(alpha=0.0,beta=0.0,tau2=1.0))
#inits.JAGS = function(){
  #return(list(alpha=rnorm(1),beta=rnorm(1),tau2=rgamma(0.1,0.1)))
#}

Now we set which parameters were going to simulate with our MCMC model:

para.JAGS = c("alpha","beta","tau2","sigma2")

And, we fit the model:

fit.JAGS = jags(data=data.JAGS,inits=inits.JAGS,
                parameters.to.save = para.JAGS,
                n.chains=1,
                n.iter=9000,
                n.burnin=1000,
                model.file=linear.model.JAGS)

This completes the code for the simple regression model. We can now make inferences and evaluate our model.

First, you can summarize the results. We will print the fit summary, and plot the parameter coefficient estimates as an rjags object and as an mcmc object.

We can also generate a simple plot as an rjags object, but as we will see below, there are more effective visualizations. This plot display the medians with an 80% interval bar.

plot(fit.JAGS)

Now we generate a traceplot to evaluate whether we are efficiently exploring the parameter space and sampling from the stationary distribution.

traceplot(fit.JAGS,mfrow=c(2,3),ask=FALSE)

We can also plot as an MCMC object, which shows all the parameter densities along with their traceplots.

fit.JAGS.mcmc = as.mcmc(fit.JAGS)
plot(fit.JAGS.mcmc,ask=FALSE)

We can also summarize as an MCMC object.

And we can trace plot as an MCMC object.

xyplot(fit.JAGS.mcmc,layout=c(2,3))

We can also density plot as an MCMC object.

densityplot(fit.JAGS.mcmc)

This completes our analysis of our first Bayesian regression model, together with basic diagnostics. Well talk later about model checking and more severe model assessments.
